\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Each Component Under Load\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Vercel \'97 essentially infinitely scalable
\f0\b0  Vercel runs on serverless functions. When traffic spikes, it automatically spins up more instances. There's no server that gets overwhelmed. Netflix-scale companies run on this architecture. Hundreds of uploads a week is nothing \'97 you'd need millions of concurrent users before Vercel became a concern.\

\f2\b Mux \'97 built for exactly this
\f0\b0  Mux's entire product is high-volume video. They handle encoding, storage, and streaming for companies like Robinhood, PBS, and Patreon. Hundreds of videos a week is a rounding error for them. Their HLS adaptive streaming automatically adjusts quality based on viewer connection speed. This scales to millions of concurrent viewers without you touching anything.\

\f2\b Cloudflare R2 \'97 scales automatically
\f0\b0  R2 is Cloudflare's object storage. Cloudflare runs on 300+ data points globally. Photos get served from the edge closest to the viewer. Hundreds of uploads a week, millions of views \'97 no configuration needed, it just handles it.\

\f2\b Supabase \'97 scales well to a point
\f0\b0  This is the one component that needs the most attention as you grow. The free tier handles up to 500MB database and 2GB bandwidth. At hundreds of uploads a week you'll likely hit limits within a few months. The fix is simple \'97 upgrade to Supabase Pro ($25/month) which gives you 8GB database and 250GB bandwidth. That handles serious scale.\
