\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Where It Gets More Complex\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Artist portrait rights
\f0\b0  \'97 if a fan takes a close-up photo of the artist backstage, technically the artist has some rights around commercial use of their likeness. Fan sharing on a community platform is generally considered fair use/editorial. Selling or licensing that photo is where it gets complicated.\

\f2\b Venue restrictions
\f0\b0  \'97 some venues explicitly prohibit photography in certain areas (backstage, production areas) in their ticketing terms. If someone violated venue rules to get the content, that's a terms of service issue between them and the venue \'97 not really your problem as the platform hosting it, similar to how YouTube isn't liable for content that violates a venue's photography policy.\

\f2\b Professional camera restrictions
\f0\b0  \'97 many venues ban professional cameras but allow phone cameras. Most backstage passes have similar language. Again this is between the attendee and the venue.\

\f2\b Confidential/private areas
\f0\b0  \'97 if someone snuck into a genuinely private area (artist's personal dressing room without permission) that's a different matter. But legitimate backstage pass holders are explicitly allowed to be there.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 How Platforms Handle This\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 YouTube, TikTok, Instagram \'97 they all host backstage fan content constantly and don't proactively police it. They respond to takedown requests when rights holders complain.\
Your DMCA page (which you just built in Phase 6.3) is exactly the right mechanism. If an artist or venue objects to specific content, they submit a DMCA request and you remove it. You're not liable for hosting it in good faith before receiving notice.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The Opportunity\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Backstage content is actually a huge differentiator for Showside. Nobody else has it organized. A fan with a meet & greet photo or a backstage clip has nowhere to put it that's contextually relevant to the show. Right now it goes on Instagram and gets lost.\
On Showside it lives on the event page tagged as "Meet & Greet" or "Backstage" \'97 permanent, findable, part of the show's record.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The Taxonomy Already Supports It\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Looking back at the content taxonomy we built \'97 "Meet & greet" is already in the concert-specific tags. You're already set up for this. No product changes needed.\
The only thing worth adding to your terms of service is a line that uploaders confirm they had legitimate access to the location where they captured their content. That shifts liability to the uploader, which is standard for any UGC platform.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

